segments.text: Is it possible for your mom to tell me a little more about life in Mexico and the trip to Mexico to the United States?
Is it possible, ma'am?
Su historia de muchos años pesados.
El viaje de Texas.
Pues, mira, lo que yo sé, te voy a decir un poquito, de cuando vino ella aquí a estos estados.
Sí.
Bueno, según yo he oído platicar, ella también lo sabe, nomás que ahorita no se acuerda.
Mire, mamá, lo que le quiere decir ella es cómo vino a dar...
Here in Texas.
You told me, and I know, my uncle first came here to the States, right?
The one with my mom?
Yes.
Well, that's what she wants to know.
In that one in St. Rice that there was, at the beginning of Puras Pastas, he was the one who came to give here.
And he was the one who, without the help of us, took us.
Yes.
My uncle was the first?
Yes.
And who else?
My uncle Atanasio and my uncle Bernardo.
They were already here.
They had a lot of time here, I think.
Brothers of you or your husband?
No, he was my mother's little brother.
Brother of your mother?
Yes, my mother's little brother.
And he comes first?
Where was your mother born?
Well, I don't know where my mother would have been born.
But she is from Mexico.
She is from Mexico.
Yes.
Well, that place where I am from, I think that place would be her as well.
I don't know.
Yes.
Well, tell me about this trip.
In what way did you come?
By bus?
By train?
But don't you remember the trip?
Well, the trip when he brought us here.
Yes, the trip here.
Mom, you... Look, according to that...
I don't know, my husband is the one who fixed everything.
Mom, what she wants to say, mom, is that you came here hired.
I don't know anything, Lupe.
I saw your father and he didn't tell me to see my mother.
He went through the bridge.
Look, they went through, you know, look, that's what I know.
They came, they came because my uncle.
Yes.
And he was uncle on behalf of his mother, of her sister.
Yes.
See?
He was our uncle, who has been her brother-in-law.
Yes.
Well.
Y luego, un hermanito de su cuñado de ella vino, fueron los primeros que vinieron pa' Texas.
Sí.
Bueno.
Según eso, ellos venían, trajeron familias contratadas de México pa' acá.
Sí.
Y que pagaban nomás la pasada.
Ellos pasaron por el puente y pagaban un nicle.
Sí.
Ándale.
En la fuente.
En el puente.
Eso sé lo que me acuerdo que me platicaban los abuelitos y mi tío.

Bueno, entonces cuando ya estaban los tíos aquí, fueron para atrás, ya ellos habían hecho poco dinerito aquí, y ellos ya sabían, pero de ahí para allá yo no sé cómo vendrían ellos, pero ellos decían que pasaban por el puente y daban un nicle, ¿ves?
Bueno, entonces ellos ya se enteraron todo cómo estaba aquí, entonces fueron por mi...
mi abuelito y mi abuelita y mi mamá que es ella y mi papá entonces vinieron todos ellos juntos y luego una hermanita de mi abuelita también y entonces se vino su
su esposo de mi tía mía también con ellos.
Esas dos personas los trajeron a ellos.
Y no nomás a ellos, mucha gente, porque los trajeron contratados, una persona, no sé quién.
¿Ves?
Pero de esas gentes de los trabajos.
Sí, estaba mucha gente en este grupo.
Ándale.
Sí.
Pero Guadalajara está muy lejos de Texas.
¿En qué modo?
Caminando por Texas?
O en qué modo fueron?
Oh, ese sí.
Este, bueno, te juro que eso sí, no, no, no te doy razón yo.
De allí, ¿sabes en dónde estuvieron?
Por eso no caminaron mucho.
Entonces, ellos pasaron y estuvieron en... Brunsville.
Brunsville.
Cheype.
En Cheype.
Yes, there is a little town called Brozville, Cheipe.
I think they used to call it Cheipe, but now it's Brozville.
It's a prison.
They were working there with my family.
They made money to walk there.
So when they got there, they were working there, all that group.
So they were making the cut.
They were barely making the cut.
I think it was, now you'll see, it was from Limburgo.
In Limburgo.
That's where they arrived, they were just making the cut.
They were making it when they arrived.
Then from there, I don't know how long they would last there, so they brought them here to this place of Tlalcuta, yes, everything was Puro Monte.
Entonces, estaba la tienda que le decían el señor Barras.
Que yo no sé qué será de la señora.
Where are you?
What's the lady's name?
I don't know if her father owned that store.
All these people there were dealing with that man.
Everyone was going there with that man who had a very big store that they had already taken away.
All these people were going there with him.
very close to my father and my uncles and my grandparents and everything.
Ay, with that man.
I think that my grandmother was
Real de Oro.
Real de Oro.
Yes, because my grandmother was what she said.
Yes.
Real de Oro.
Well, you married in Real de Oro, right?
Yes, I married in Real de Pozos.
Real de Pozos.
Real de pozos.
Real de pozos y real de loros, y así le decían.
O sea, cuál será, pero allí decía mi abuelita.
Sí.
Minerales.
Es bonito allá.
Puros cerros.
Puros cerros.
No, puros cerros.
¿Cómo te pasa?
Cerros, cerros, muchos cerros.
Y el pueblo está sentado abajo.
Up there, you can only see hills.
Yes.
If you look to the side, there are puddles of water that come down here.
Yes.
All hills.
Pure hills.
Yes.
And down there is the town.
Did you live in the town?
No.
No?
Here on the banks where the mines were.
Near the mines?
Yes, yes.
On the back of the hills were the houses.
And the village was down there.
What kind of houses?
Well, you know, houses of the poor.
Houses of stone, and also with earth.
But they were earthen houses, with terraces and rooms.
Yes, that's right.
They make houses out of grass.
They make houses out of...
They make houses out of...
They make houses out of...
They make houses out of...
They make houses out of...
They make houses out of...
They make houses out of...
They make houses out of...
They make houses out of...
Tortillas to sell, my grandmother.
Yes.
In Mexico?
In Mexico, yes.
Yes, because I was afraid of one.
Is there enough to eat there in Mexico?
Yes, but look at the money.
Well, yes, for your family there was enough to eat.
There is no money for the poor people, there is no work, there is nothing.
There is nothing?
There is no work?
There are parts where there is no work.
My father used to pay 50 cents a day to clean the mines.
50 cents a day.
And your husband too?
No, my father, when he was living next to my father, he earned 50 cents.
Above the mine.
There was a mine of what material?
Of copper or silver or what?
Of pure silver.
Silver?
Silver and gold and everything.
But look, they were all beating them up before they left because they didn't want anything to happen to them.
Every time they were beaten up, they were punished.
All the doormen were at the door when they left work.
They were beating them up.
And what kind of work did your husband have?
Your husband?
No, he was at the ranch all the time.
Ah, so he wasn't at the mines, only your father?
No, my father who worked at the mine.
Was the life at the ranch better than the life at the mine?
Yes, it was better.
Why?
Because I don't know why life at the ranch was better.
Because they raised the chickens, they raised the sheep, they raised one who helped.
Y en los minas fue posible tener gallinas.
Allí no hay nada de eso, más de puro trabajo del esposo.
No hay comidas para... No, no hay nada.
Pura piedra.
Pura piedra.
Pura piedra.
Y no hay toantes o nada.
Vas tú al agua, a los cerros.
Sí.
O trae el agua a los cerros y aquí no estamos de cerca, entero de una estela para acá.
Ahí.
Acá arriba el agua de Tamar.
Sí.
Ahí, muy duro.
There's no water nearby, right?
No, there's no water nearby.
Was it necessary to bring water?
Yes, from the hills.
For a long distance?
No, not very far.
It's the side of the hills where you go to swim.
After you got married, did you live on the ranch or in Nena?
No, we lived on the ranch.
Until the first time, we lived on the ranch.
No neighbors or anything, just the ranch.
Yes, all the time, just the ranch.
Yes, because my father was, all the time since he got married, he was a worker at the ranch.
Oh, your father, your father, you never lived on the mills.
No, they live in the ranch, but your father was alone.
Alone, alone in the ranch.
Alone, alone, without his mother.
Yes.
And you and your mother and the other children live all the time in the ranch.
Only ranch, yes.
Only ranch.
No, because my mother was my daughter.
Only her daughters had my grandparents.
Only her.
Just her.
She and my other aunt.
Just two.
Two women.
But my other aunt got married in Mexico and she was with my grandmother.
Mi abuelito todo el tiempo iba a la mina, pero ellas allí tenían su lugar como aquí, pero mi abuelito iba donde estaba la mina a trabajar.
Mi mamá se casó, mi papá no iba a la mina, iba a la labor todo el tiempo.
Mi papá todo el tiempo le gustó allá en México y aquí trabajar en la labor.
Nunca en las minas.
No, he was always like that.
But your grandfather was a miner?
Yes, my grandfather was a miner.
Did your grandfather's father also work in the mines?
No, the father of...
The father of your father, mom.
The father of your father?
No, he worked in another mountain range.
Another mountain range?
Yes, because he came to see us.
He came from another mountain range, I never knew.
He came to visit us and bring us any gift from over there.
Yes.
But I didn't know where he was going.
It's just hills and mountains.
Yes, but his work is in the mines too?
No, only my father does it.
Only your father?
Yes, I don't know.
His grandfather is... his grandfather?
Yes, grandfather, but he doesn't...
He's filling all those mountains over there.
Pure beings, far away.
Was he a cappuccino or what?
The work in the labors?
Well, I think he also worked in the labors, who knows.
I think, you didn't know him, that he came there?
Yes, because he came to see us.
I never heard his voice, never.
No, I didn't hear anything.
No, because he came to see us, to visit us.
But two or three days later, he was coming back.
We were never right about your farm, your house, no.
And your ranch, was it beautiful?
The grandfather's.
And you, mom, where did you live?
Oh, my little ranch is like here.
One ranch here, another one over there, and so on.
All the ranches are removed.
No, mom, she wants to tell you how we have it here, right?
How was your place where you were?
Clean, beautiful, something that you had there.
Well, yes, beautiful trees and everything.
Tuna poles, and well, when it was time.
Yes.
Yes.
A lot of cranes, a lot of tarpaulins, a lot of tarpaulins.
Well, like here, there's a lot of that.
Did you go back to Mexico again since you came to the United States?
No, my mom never went.
I don't think I even know.
I don't think I even know where to go.
Nothing.
Nothing?
I fell like a stone in the well.
I never got there.
My father never knew about his father, or his mother, or his brothers.
My father never knew anything.
And they made money and they didn't try to go.
Because since they didn't have papers to fix, they didn't fix it at that time.
They didn't fix it, since they didn't bother them, they never fixed it.
So, my father never went there.
No one went there.
Not even my brothers have fixed it yet.
Because they grew up here.
My brother already fixed it, he has everything.
But he still doesn't want to move there.
But my mother never went.
She came here and she didn't know where to go.
There is sadness sometimes for your home in Mexico.
You, you, you think, mom, in Mexico.
You have always thought, mom, that, as Juanita says, what aunt wouldn't want to come to Mexico, mom?
No, no.
I mean, I don't have there, all those who stayed, who were people of my husband, they were dead, they were in the war, God knows, they would kill, God knows.
My whole family saw that it was my mother and my father.
It was my whole family.
Yes, your mother and father and everything was quiet.
I would go to see my mother-in-law.
He never did the duty of leaving.
When I got there, I got upset.
I said, well, I was saving money to go to Mexico and he never did the duty of leaving.
Well, it's worth not saying anything.
I never went out again.
Never, never.
He lost everything.
Everything ended up in Mexico.
But I don't think mom wants to go to her country because, since we haven't arranged a permit for her, she can go because she's been here for years.
Yes, but I don't like it here in Mexico.
I don't think so.
Well, I don't know.
Because all the time that I was in California, I really like it there because I have a lot of friends there, I have my children, and I would like to go there.
But she has her family here in the same place.
But I'm going to see her.
Yes.
I don't even have to go.
I'm happy to go to see my uncle, to see my uncle.
I don't have anyone.
That's why I'm leaving.
I don't want to go to Mexico.
Even if I die, I'll stay here.
No, I'm not going.
I have a friend who went to Mexico.
I think he's in San Luis Potosi.
It was the two of them, the two men in their truck.
Y ellos, dice mi compadre, comadre, hacía muchos años que yo no iba allí.
Dice, y siempre fui reconociendo, dice, de tantos años hay cosas que todavía hay cuando yo existía allá y que estaba joven.
Dice, y me siento contento, dice, porque todavía hay cosas cuando yo estaba, mi tío y mis hermanas y...
And she says, I feel very good.
But if I go, I will look everywhere.
I don't have anyone.
Yes, mom, but when you go, mom, and you look at one thing, you...
you will feel happy because you say, no, I'm happy, I will feel like crying.
Well, both things.
Because the heart is never happy.
As you wish, but there are things that one reflects in those times, be it with sadness, or it has to give it sadness and pleasure, but as you wish.
That's what my mother says.
No, because I know she doesn't.
Because I have to refuse my mother, my husband, and all that.
Do you believe that?
No.
This heart can't.
This is her land now.
For many years.
Yes.
Because her mother stayed here, and her father stayed here, and my father stayed here, and all her children stayed here.
Yes.
That's why I tell you, I will never go to Mexico.
I go to California and I say, because of these places I walked with my children, because of these places I was very anxious, because of these paths I walked, and we all walked together.
And now I go alone.
Now that I went, I went with the two, well, the three, with the daughter-in-law.
There are times that I go only with Janie and Asina, and you always feel sad.
You feel sad for life, right?
Yes.
My life has been very sad.
Your life has been very sad?
All my life.
Lupe has always been like that.
His life has always been sad.
I felt more about my children than I felt about my husband.
I don't think a husband feels like that.
I don't think a husband feels like that.
And a husband who does well with one, will cry until he dies, like it happened to me.
My husband was very good to me and his children.
Mom struggled a lot here because she didn't have a stove, she didn't have anything.
She would put the baths in the fire and she would put a lot of tortillas and everything she did.
And I, you know where I grew up?
She used to put one of those little beds that they used to make.
Like this, in squares, a canvas and a square, that's how they used to make it.
And they used to put it there, and they used to put me there, and I would get wet, the air was the one that would get me wet.
Yes.
It was there.
There was a stick, it was her crib.
A stick, and she would hang it on the crib and roll it there.
I never went to the hospital, I never went to the doctor, I never did anything.
I got married and now I've been to the hospital twice.
Y esta última vez que yo estuve en el hospital, yo me sentí muy a gusto.
Porque nunca había descansado como descansé ese día, esas veces que estuve en el hospital.
Yo creo que estuve tres semanas.
Hasta entonces, descansé de tan mi larga vida a trabajar.
¿Ves?
Y eso es... No, me salió de buenas vidas y buenos pensamientos.
Sí.
Because she gave birth to her whole family.
I know you gave birth to both of your children.
They got married a year ago.
Two years ago, right?
You gave birth to both of your children.
They came out of here like a little lady.
They got married.
And a lot of very fine children.
That's a good thing in life.
I think.
And you also had 12.
Twelve children?
Yes, twelve children.
And all of them lived?
Yes, all of them were taken away by God.
And my family was taken away too.
Only three of them stayed with me.
I was the only one who was married.
I was the only daughter of my mother.
And I was the only one who was married.
You?
Yes, I was the only one who was married.
There were twelve children and only one was married?
Yes, my two brothers.
Oh, two brothers.
We were two brothers and a woman, and two men.
From twelve to only three I got married.
For what reason did you never get married, your children, your other children?
Well, they lasted a long time, my mother, my brothers.
The youngest had seventeen years.
The youngest of her sisters.
How old is your sister?
17 years old.
17 years old.
She's young.
But she died.
But they died.
I don't have any more sisters, only my two brothers.
Your two brothers?
Yes.
And they are married?
She was 17 years old when she died, the youngest.
Oh, she still died?
Yes, yes.
My brothers are married.
Two brothers and how many sisters?
There were twelve.
Twelve.
There were eight.
Ten.
Ten sisters.
There are ten daughters.
No fueron ocho, porque los otros son hombres, bebitos.
Ocho mujeres y cuatro hombres.
Y dos hombres vivían y se casaron.
Pero de estas mujeres solamente una se casó.
Y las otras, ¿dónde viven las otras?
They all died.
All the little ones and the big ones, they all died.
I was the only one left as a woman.
Of all the sisters, only me.
And my two sisters.
All the sisters died.
They are sisters.
But where did these big sisters live?
Oh, they were with my mom all the time.
All the time?
Yes, with my dad.
Ah, also.
Now they live together.
They filled a table like this one for another family.
Ah, yes.
Yes.
Well, for what reason did these others never get married?
No, they left, they came back.
To the world, my daughters.
They never...
They were not dancers, they were not of any taste.
Well, maybe, for what reason did you get married?
Well, so you can see, because I was the first one to get married.
The first one to come, and the first one to get married.
Oh, yes.
Yes.
But my sisters, look, they lasted a long time.
Yes.
No, mi hermanita.
Mi hermanita, la más chica que todas, ella tenía 15 años cuando se casó.
Hay otra.
Ah, otra.
Otra, pero ella se fue con el esposo para México.
Ah, sí.
¿De qué parte de México?
Ahí está en el 18 de marzo.
Sí.
Ahí es donde está ella, al otro de Matamoros.
Sí.
Allá está ella, pero ella ya se murió.
Ella no está, mi hermana.
No?
No.
We haven't seen my sister or anything.
Because she left in...
I don't know if it was in 1941 or 1942, she left with my sister.
And she never writes or anything?
No, she's already dead.
She died.
She died.
She left two children.
Yes.
Yes, now there's one here in...
Near Amarillo there is a nephew who is the son of my sister.
Yes.
There he is.
He only left two men and a woman.
But it ended so well.
And there they are now.
First when they left, now it is beautiful.
Yes, now it is beautiful.
Have you never been to that place in Mexico?
Have you been to Mexico?
I know a lot of places in Mexico.
I lived for three months in Urapán, Michoacán.
It's a beautiful town.
Very beautiful.
It's very beautiful.
The state of Guadalajara, I think, is very beautiful.
The mountains are beautiful, the trees, the fields are green.
Yes, I like Mexico very much.
The land is very beautiful.
The land is very beautiful.
Yes, Mexico is very beautiful.
What happens is that the poor people have to come here to look for a better way to live.
That's what happens.
Like us going to California.
I went because I really liked to know.
I had never been there.
Me gustaba porque allá pagaban más, me gustaba porque aquí no había nada.
Allá te cansas tú, mejor te cansas tú de trabajar, que el trabajo se acabe.
Necesitas tú decir, ya me cansé, o decir, estoy malo, porque en esos estados todo el tiempo hay trabajo.
Solo en invierno duras dos, tres meses.
that there is no work because of the winter, but not because of it.
In California, only the water or the cold was removed, and you are going to step on the cotton.
Yes, there is a time here that there is a lack of work.
Yes.
In winter, or what time?
Here?
Yes, in Texas.
Well, here in Texas there is no January, December, October and all that.
Many months.
Many months, yes.
That's why you had to go.
Those who want to go, they go to where there is work.
And I left because I wanted to go to other states.
I worked there alone and I had a lot of money to support my kids because I earned 10 pesos a day.
So 10 pesos a day
I did it very well with the boys, and then two or three days that they were off, they worked.
And they paid them very well, so that we worked very well.
And here, where do you work?
Here there was not enough work.
Only the pizca season and that was it.
In Washington, it's the same.
In winter, it's hard in Washington.
But if you work in Washington for three or four months, you get the same job.
And you earn more, twice as much.
Yes, we have to go all the way to Mexico.
We're not going anywhere.
That's why I liked it a lot.
It's the same as here.
It's like a ranch.
I don't ask about anything because I don't know.
It's like a ranch.
Was there a owner in the ranch over there?
We came from over there to come here.
From Sunrise to the ranch.
To build one in the ranch.
She's talking about your boss, mom.
Did you work with a boss?
In Mexico?
Yes, my husband did.
What's the name of your husband's boss in Mexico?
Do you remember?
I don't even remember.
It's been a long time.
His name was Abundo Ayala.
What?
Abundo.
Abundo Ayala.
Abundo Ayala.
Abundio Ayala.
Ayala was the boss.
It was a farm there where my husband worked.
It was a farm?
What was the name of the farm?
I don't know, but the owner was Abundo Ayala.
Abundo Ayala.
That's where my husband worked with him.
They didn't live there because of the fire.
The one in Hacienda is called Rancho Grande.
Yes, I understand.
The one in Hacienda is called Rancho Grande.
It's just that it's different from what they say here.
And Mr. Ayala, what happened to him?
Who knows?
Who knows, but we came here.
God knows, they will live, they will die, God knows.
No, well, if they lived, you realize that if I went over there and stayed with the place, I would go down to my house, because that's where we came from.
That's where they lived since they got married?
Yes, that's where they worked.
He was a horse herder, a horse herder of animals, he did all the work there.
He would be stronger, I don't know.
My father liked a lot to tie the horses or whatever, and to knock them down.
He wasn't afraid of the animals.
He had a lot of courage for that.
Yes.
He really liked to eat manganese and manzanas and everything.
He really liked the tobacco.
And does he want to leave the farm?
In those days, his mom and dad went to Texas.
Does his husband really want to go to Texas too?
To go to Texas too?
Well, they don't exist anymore.
They all died.
They don't exist anymore.
But they never went, they never went to the west, to Mexico.
No, they don't want to go.
They never wanted to go.
They wanted to go, but they didn't.
I don't know.
I still go because my husband never said, let's go to Mexico.
And I, a very poor person, told him, let's gather money little by little and let's go to Mexico.
Because he had all his people in Monterrey.
No, no.
And now, he didn't want to say that we were going in a bus, because we had a car.
No, never.
And now that I'm alone, my boy, Rudy, let's go to Mexico, mom.
Let's go.
This girl who is in Pennsylvania, now that she came, we went two or three times to Laredo.
And Juanita also took me to Mexico.
And no...
Ya de hora que nosotros tenemos carros, vamos pa' todas partes.
Sí.
Y ahora dice, ahora que me den las vacaciones, vamos pa' California.
Le digo, pues sí, sí, vamos.
That's why the thought, the person has it since they were little.
When she was in low grade, all the time she would tell me, mom, when I grow up, let's say I'm a girl and I finish school and go to work.
I'm going to buy a car, she would say, and then I'll take her everywhere for a walk, she would say.

And I tell her, look, it seems that God granted you, because now that she finished her school, she then bought her first cart, and now she bought another cart, and she takes me everywhere, wherever I tell her to go, I just tell her...
Get out of work and let's go.
See?
God granted us, He granted you to take us for a walk.
Yes.
Yes.
Well, this is one of the most interesting stories I've heard.
You've heard.
Yes.
And thank you very much.
Yes, well, look, I have had, as it was that my boy, I lost him, right?
Yes.
I wanted very much to see for myself
La historia de su vida.
Y fue lo que me dijo mi muchacho, mamá, usted debió de haber puesto en el papel, dijo, la historia de la vida de mi hermano.
Y le dije, pues sí, pero como yo no sé leer, si yo supiera leer, cállate.
Yo estoy, estoy, estoy, estoy de todo.
